   <titles>
      <title>Basis - Explanation</title>
   </titles>
   <body>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>Let’s examine a bit what the concept of a basis really means.</para.body>
            </para>
            <para>
               <para.body>The first condition: <math>
                     <latex>\EuScript{B}</latex>
                  </math> spans <math>
                     <latex>V</latex>
                  </math> means that every vector <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                  </math> in <math>
                     <latex>V</latex>
                  </math> can be expressed in some way as a linear combination of vectors in <math>
                     <latex>\EuScript{B}</latex>
                  </math>:</para.body>
            </para>
            <math.array column="3">
               <row rowspan="1">
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <text>=</text>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>t_1\Vect{b}_1 + \cdots + t_k\Vect{b}_k</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
               </row>
            </math.array>
            <para>
               <para.body>with <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{b}_1, \dots ,\Vect{b}_k</latex>
                  </math> in <math>
                     <latex>\EuScript{B}</latex>
                  </math> and <math>
                     <latex>t_1, \dots ,t_k</latex>
                  </math> in <math>
                     <latex>\RNr</latex>
                  </math>. – Now, if there is one way of expressing <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                  </math> as a linear combination of vectors in <math>
                     <latex>\EuScript{B}</latex>
                  </math>, there might be many ways of doing so. This is where the second requirement for a basis comes in:</para.body>
            </para>
            <para>
               <para.body>
                  <math>
                     <latex>\EuScript{B}</latex>
                  </math> is linearly independent. This means that if <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                  </math> can be expressed as a linear combination of vectors in <math>
                     <latex>\EuScript{B}</latex>
                  </math>, then there is exactly one way of doing so.</para.body>
            </para>
            <para>
               <para.body>The two conditions combined, then, tell us that every vector in <math>
                     <latex>V</latex>
                  </math> can be expressed in exactly one way as a linear combination of vectors in <math>
                     <latex>\EuScript{B}</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
